President Biden has declared a major disaster in South Dakota due to severe storms, straight-line winds, tornadoes, and flooding that occurred on May 12, 2022. Federal assistance will be provided to supplement state, tribal, and local recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be available for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities on a cost-sharing basis. The counties of Aurora, Beadle, Bon Homme, Brookings, Clay, Codington, Day, Deuel, Grant, Hamlin, Hanson, Hutchinson, Kingsbury, Lake, McCook, Miner, Minnehaha, Moody, Roberts, and Turner, as well as the Flandreau Santee Sioux Tribe and the Sisseton-Wahpeton Oyate, are eligible for assistance. Hazard mitigation measures statewide will also be eligible for funding. Alana B. Kuhn has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations, and additional designations may be made in the future based on further damage assessments. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk.